I mean, we go to cinemas and watch movies  hoping we'd be entertained and would feel good after (NOT to be heartbroken and feeling sad.)   I love everything in the movie except the ending. text: I read the book.  It's not romantic.  It's a tragedy.  I will never take a cent from Will's money to spend on travelling and drinking tea in Paris.  I will donate everything to the "Yellow Ribbon" to prevent others to commit euthanasia.  And give the fund to any medical research discovery to cure any spinal cord injury.  My Mother has an elephantiasis since 1968.  If she had chosen to just end her life, because she no longer wants to suffer and be a burden to others, we wouldn't be here.  Other people may find my life worth ending, but I was raised to believe that for as long as you live there is "HOPE".  Israel's national anthem is HaTikva.  The HOPE.  Can you imagine that there are people to this day with a mentality that euthanasia is a mercy killing.  I agree with Lou's Mother.  If Clarke truly loves Will she wouldn't go to Switzerland to support his desire to end the life of pain and sufferings for being in a wheelchair for the rest of his life.  Will is selfish and full of pride.
